[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/data-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The Xerox Network Systems Courier technology in the early 1980s influenced the first widely adopted standard.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Sun Microsystems published the External Data Representation (XDR) in 1987.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] XDR is an open format, and standardized as STD 67 (RFC 4506) by IETF.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In the late 1990s, a push to provide an alternative to the standard serialization protocols started: XML, an SGML subset, was used to produce a human-readable text-based encoding.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Such an encoding can be useful for persistent objects that may be read and understood by humans or communicated to other systems regardless of programming language.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] It has the disadvantage of losing the more compact, byte-stream-based encoding, but by this point larger storage and transmission capacities made file size less of a concern than in the early days of computing.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In the 2000s, XML was often used for asynchronous transfer of structured data between client and server in Ajax web applications.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] XML is an open format and standardized as a W3C recommendation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] JSON is a lightweight plain-text alternative to XML and is also commonly used for client-server communication in web applications.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] JSON is based on JavaScript syntax but is independent of JavaScript and supported in many other programming languages.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] YAML is a strict superset of JSON and includes additional features such as a data type tags, support for cyclic data structures, indentation-sensitive syntax, and multiple forms of scalar data quoting.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Property lists are used for serialization by NeXTSTEP, GNUstep, macOS, and iOS frameworks.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] *Property list*, or *p-list* for short, doesn't refer to a single serialization format but instead several different variants, some human-readable and one binary.
