[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Several object-oriented programming languages directly support *object serialization* (or *object archival*), either by syntactic sugar elements or providing a standard interface for doing so.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The languages which do so include Ruby, Smalltalk, Python, PHP, Objective-C, Delphi, Java, and the .NET family of languages.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There are also libraries available that add serialization support to languages that lack native support for it.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] C and C++ do not provide serialization as any sort of high-level construct, but both languages support writing any of the built-in data types, as well as plain old data structs, as binary data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] As such, it is usually trivial to write custom serialization functions.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Moreover, compiler-based solutions, such as the ODB ORM system for C++ and the gSOAP toolkit for C and C++, are capable of automatically producing serialization code with few or no modifications to class declarations.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Other popular serialization frameworks are Boost.Serialization from the Boost Framework, the S11n framework, and Cereal.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] MFC framework (Microsoft) also provides serialization methodology as part of its Document-View architecture.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] With the introduction of reflective programming to C++26, serialization has been greatly simplified.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Reflection allows for compile-time serialization of, for instance, JSON into a `struct` with corresponding structure.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] CFML allows data structures to be serialized to WDDX with the `<cfwddx>` tag and to JSON with the SerializeJSON() function.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Delphi provides a built-in mechanism for serialization of components (also called persistent objects), which is fully integrated with its IDE.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The component's contents are saved to a DFM file and reloaded on-the-fly.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Go natively supports unmarshalling/marshalling of JSON and XML data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There are also third-party modules that support YAML and Protocol Buffers.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In Haskell, serialization is supported for types that are members of the Read and Show type classes.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Every type that is a member of the `Read` type class defines a function that will extract the data from the string representation of the dumped data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The `Show` type class, in turn, contains the `show` function from which a string representation of the object can be generated.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The programmer need not define the functions explicitly—merely declaring a type to be deriving Read or deriving Show, or both, can make the compiler generate the appropriate functions for many cases (but not all: function types, for example, cannot automatically derive Show or Read).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The auto-generated instance for Show also produces valid source code, so the same Haskell value can be generated by running the code produced by show in, for example, a Haskell interpreter.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For more efficient serialization, there are haskell libraries that allow high-speed serialization in binary format, e.g. binary.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Java provides automatic serialization which requires that the object be marked by implementing the `java.io.Serializable` interface.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Implementing the interface marks the class as "okay to serialize", and Java then handles serialization internally.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There are no serialization methods defined on the `Serializable` interface, but a serializable class can optionally define methods with certain special names and signatures that if defined, will be called as part of the serialization/deserialization process.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The language also allows the developer to override the serialization process more thoroughly by implementing another interface, the `Externalizable` interface, which includes two special methods that are used to save and restore the object's state.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There are three primary reasons why objects are not serializable by default and must implement the `Serializable` interface to access Java's serialization mechanism.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Firstly, not all objects capture useful semantics in a serialized state.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For example, a `Thread` object is tied to the state of the current JVM.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There is no context in which a deserialized `Thread` object would maintain useful semantics.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Secondly, the serialized state of an object forms part of its class' compatibility contract.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Maintaining compatibility between versions of serializable classes requires additional effort and consideration.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Therefore, making a class serializable needs to be a deliberate design decision and not a default condition.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Lastly, serialization allows access to non-transient private members of a class that are not otherwise accessible.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Classes containing sensitive information (for example, a password) should not be serializable nor externalizable.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The standard encoding method uses a recursive graph-based translation of the object's class descriptor and serializable fields into a byte stream.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Primitives as well as non-transient, non-static referenced objects are encoded into the stream.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Each object that is referenced by the serialized object via a field that is not marked as `transient` must also be serialized; and if any object in the complete graph of non-transient object references is not serializable, then serialization will fail.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The developer can influence this behavior by marking objects as transient, or by redefining the serialization for an object so that some portion of the reference graph is truncated and not serialized.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Java does not use constructor to serialize objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] It is possible to serialize Java objects through JDBC and store them into a database.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] While Swing components do implement the Serializable interface, they are not guaranteed to be portable between different versions of the Java Virtual Machine.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] As such, a Swing component, or any component which inherits it, may be serialized to a byte stream, but it is not guaranteed that this will be re-constitutable on another machine.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Since ECMAScript 5.1, JavaScript has included the built-in `JSON` object and its methods `JSON.parse()` and `JSON.stringify()`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Although JSON is originally based on a subset of JavaScript, there are boundary cases where JSON is not valid JavaScript.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Specifically, JSON allows the Unicode line terminators U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR and U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR to appear unescaped in quoted strings, while ECMAScript 2018 and older does not.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Julia implements serialization through the `serialize()` / `deserialize()` modules, intended to work within the same version of Julia, and/or instance of the same system image.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The `HDF5.jl` package offers a more stable alternative, using a documented format and common library with wrappers for different languages, while the default serialization format is suggested to have been designed rather with maximal performance for network communication in mind.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Generally a Lisp data structure can be serialized with the functions "`read`" and "`print`".
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] A variable foo containing, for example, a list of arrays would be printed by `(print foo)`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Similarly an object can be read from a stream named s by `(read s)`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] These two parts of the Lisp implementation are called the Printer and the Reader.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The output of "`print`" is human readable; it uses lists demarked by parentheses, for example: `(4 2.9 "x" y)`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In many types of Lisp, including Common Lisp, the printer cannot represent every type of data because it is not clear how to do so.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In Common Lisp for example the printer cannot print CLOS objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Instead the programmer may write a method on the generic function `print-object`, this will be invoked when the object is printed.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] This is somewhat similar to the method used in Ruby.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Lisp code itself is written in the syntax of the reader, called read syntax.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Most languages use separate and different parsers to deal with code and data, Lisp only uses one.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] A file containing lisp code may be read into memory as a data structure, transformed by another program, then possibly executed or written out, such as in a read–eval–print loop.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Not all readers/writers support cyclic, recursive or shared structures.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] .NET has several serializers designed by Microsoft.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There are also many serializers by third parties.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] OCaml's standard library provides marshalling through the `Marshal` module and the Pervasives functions `output_value` and `input_value`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] While OCaml programming is statically type-checked, uses of the `Marshal` module may break type guarantees, as there is no way to check whether an unmarshalled stream represents objects of the expected type.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In OCaml it is difficult to marshal a function or a data structure which contains a function (e.g. an object which contains a method), because executable code in functions cannot be transmitted across different programs.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] (There is a flag to marshal the code position of a function but it can only be unmarshalled in exactly the same program).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The standard marshalling functions can preserve sharing and handle cyclic data, which can be configured by a flag.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Several Perl modules available from CPAN provide serialization mechanisms, including `Storable` , `JSON::XS` and `FreezeThaw`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/deserialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Linux OpenGL drivers are split in two: a kernel-driver and a user-space driver.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The user-space driver does all the translation of OpenGL commands into machine code to be submitted to the GPU.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] To reduce the number of system calls, the user-space driver implements marshalling.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] If the GPU's command buffer is full of rendering data, the API could simply store the requested rendering call in a temporary buffer and, when the command buffer is close to being empty, it can perform a switch to kernel-mode and add a number of stored commands all at once.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling data requires some kind of data transfer, which leverages a specific data format to be chosen as the serialization target.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] XML is one such format and means of transferring data between systems.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Microsoft, for example, uses it as the basis of the file formats of the various components (Word, Excel, Access, PowerPoint, etc.) of the Microsoft Office suite (see Office Open XML).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] While this typically results in a verbose wire format, XML's fully-bracketed "start-tag", "end-tag" syntax allows provision of more accurate diagnostics and easier recovery from transmission or disk errors.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] In addition, because the tags occur repeatedly, one can use standard compression methods to shrink the content—all the Office file formats are created by zipping the raw XML.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Alternative formats such as JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are more concise, but correspondingly less robust for error recovery.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Once the data is transferred to a program or an application, it needs to be converted back to an object for usage.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, unmarshalling is generally used in the receiver end of the implementations of Remote Method Invocation (RMI) and Remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms to unmarshal transmitted objects in an executable form.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB or Java Architecture for XML Binding is the most common framework used by developers to marshal and unmarshal Java objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB provides for the interconversion between fundamental data types supported by Java and standard XML schema data types.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` is the framework used by C# developers to marshal and unmarshal C# objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] One of the advantages of C# over Java is that C# natively supports marshalling due to the inclusion of `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` class.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Java, on the other hand requires a non-native glue code in the form of JAXB to support marshalling.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] An example of unmarshalling is the conversion of an XML representation of an object to the default representation of the object in any programming language.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshalling is the process of converting the XML representation to the default executable Java representation, and running that very code to get a consistent, live object back.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Had a different format been chosen, the unmarshalling process would have been different, but the end result in the target runtime would be the same.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The process of unmarshalling XML data into an executable Java object is taken care of by the in-built `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` (formally `javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller`) class.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods defined in the `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` class are overloaded to accept XML from different types of input such as a `java.io.File`, `java.io.FileInputStream`, or `java.net.URL`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshal methods can deserialize an entire XML document or a small part of it.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] When the XML root element is globally declared, these methods utilize the `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext`'s mapping of XML root elements to JAXB mapped classes to initiate the unmarshalling.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] If the mappings are not sufficient and the root elements are declared locally, the unmarshal methods use `declaredType` methods for the unmarshalling process.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] These two approaches can be understood below.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal method uses `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext`) to unmarshal the XML data, when the root element is globally declared.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` object always maintains a mapping of the globally declared XML element and its name to a JAXB mapped class.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] If the XML element name or its `@xsi:type` attribute matches the JAXB mapped class, the unmarshal method transforms the XML data using the appropriate JAXB mapped class.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the XML element name has no match, the unmarshal process will abort and throw an `jakarta.xml.bind.UnmarshalException` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.UnmarshalException`).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] This can be avoided by using the unmarshal by `declaredType` methods.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] When the root element is not declared globally, the application assists the unmarshaller by application-provided mapping using `declaredType` parameters.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] By an order of precedence, even if the root name has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, the `declaredType` overrides the mapping.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the `@xsi:type` attribute of the XML data has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, then this takes precedence over declaredType parameter.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods by `declaredType` parameters always return a `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBElement<T>` instance.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] Schemas can be nested to represent relationships between objects (e.g. foreign key relationships).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] For example, a `Blog` may have an author represented by a `User`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] And a `User` may have many friends, each of which is a `User`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] Use a `Nested` field to represent the relationship, passing in a nested schema.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] The serialized blog will have the nested user representation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] If the field is a collection of nested objects, pass the `Nested` field to `List`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] You can explicitly specify which attributes of the nested objects you want to (de)serialize with the `only` argument to the schema.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] Dotted paths may be passed to `only` and `exclude` to specify nested attributes.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] You can replace nested data with a single value (or flat list of values if `many=True`) using the `Pluck` field.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] Nested schemas also inherit the `partial` parameter of the parent `load` call.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] You can specify a subset of the fields to allow partial loading using dot delimiters.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] If you have two objects that nest each other, you can pass a callable to `Nested`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] This allows you to resolve order-of-declaration issues, such as when one schema nests a schema that is declared below it.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] For example, a representation of an `Author` model might include the books that have a many-to-one relationship to it.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] Correspondingly, a representation of a `Book` will include its author representation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] You can also pass a class name as a string to `Nested`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] This is useful for avoiding circular imports when your schemas are located in different modules.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] If you have multiple schemas with the same class name, you must pass the full, module-qualified path.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/nesting] If the object to be marshalled has a relationship to an object of the same type, you can nest the `Schema` within itself by passing a callable that returns an instance of the same schema.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] This guide will walk you through the basics of creating schemas for serializing and deserializing data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Create a schema by defining a class with variables mapping attribute names to `Field` objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] For a full reference on the available field classes, see the `fields module documentation`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can also create a schema from a dictionary of fields using the `from_dict` method.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] `from_dict` is especially useful for generating schemas at runtime.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Serialize objects by passing them to your schema’s `dump` method, which returns the formatted result.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can also serialize to a JSON-encoded string using `dumps`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You may not need to output all declared fields every time you use a schema.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can specify which fields to output with the `only` parameter.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can also exclude fields by passing in the `exclude` parameter.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] The reverse of the `dump` method is `load`, which validates and deserializes an input dictionary to an application-level data structure.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] By default, `load` will return a dictionary of field names mapped to deserialized values (or raise a `ValidationError` with a dictionary of validation errors, which we’ll revisit later).
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Notice that the datetime string was converted to a `datetime` object.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] In order to deserialize to an object, define a method of your `Schema` and decorate it with `post_load`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] The method receives a dictionary of deserialized data.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Now, the `load` method return a `User` instance.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Set `many=True` when dealing with iterable collections of objects.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] `Schema.load` (and its JSON-decoding counterpart, `Schema.loads`) raises a `ValidationError` error when invalid data are passed in.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can access the dictionary of validation errors from the `ValidationError.messages` attribute.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] The data that were correctly deserialized are accessible in `ValidationError.valid_data`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Some fields, such as the `Email` and `URL` fields, have built-in validation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] When validating a collection, the errors dictionary will be keyed on the indices of invalid items.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can perform additional validation for a field by passing the `validate` argument.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] There are a number of built-in validators in the marshmallow.validate module.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] A validator is a callable that accepts a single argument, the value to validate.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] If validation fails, the callable should raise a `ValidationError` with an error message.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You may also pass a collection (list, tuple, generator) of callables to `validate`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Validation occurs on deserialization but not on serialization.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] To improve serialization performance, data passed to `Schema.dump` are considered valid.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can register a custom error handler function for a schema by overriding the `handle_error` method.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] See the Custom error handling page for more info.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] If you need to validate multiple fields within a single validator, see Schema-level validation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Use the `pre_load` and `post_load` field parameters.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] See Field-level pre- and post-processing.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] It is sometimes convenient to write validators as methods.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Use the `validates` decorator to register field validator methods.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can pass multiple field names to the `validates` decorator.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Make a field required by passing `required=True`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] An error will be raised if the the value is missing from the input to `Schema.load`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] To customize the error message for required fields, pass a `dict` with a `required` key as the `error_messages` argument for the field.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] When using the same schema in multiple places, you may only want to skip `required` validation by passing `partial`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] You can ignore missing fields entirely by setting `partial=True`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] `load_default` specifies the default deserialization value for a field.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Likewise, `dump_default` specifies the default serialization value.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] By default, `load` will raise a `ValidationError` if it encounters a key with no matching `Field` in the schema.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] The `unknown` option value set in `load` will override the value applied at instantiation time, which itself will override the value defined in the `class Meta`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] This order of precedence allows you to change the behavior of a schema for different contexts.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] If you only need to validate input data (without deserializing to an object), you can use `Schema.validate`.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] In the context of a web API, the `dump_only` and `load_only` parameters are conceptually equivalent to “read-only” and “write-only” fields, respectively.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] When loading, dump-only fields are considered unknown.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] If the `unknown` option is set to `INCLUDE`, values with keys corresponding to those fields are therefore loaded with no validation.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] Schemas will (de)serialize an input dictionary from/to an output dictionary whose keys are identical to the field names.
[src:marshmallow-serialize/quickstart] If you are consuming and producing data that does not match your schema, you can specify the output keys via the `data_key` argument.
